WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Mention Haiti, and this is what you'll likely hear:

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:05.920
Poverty, natural disaster, now political violence.

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:08.360
Every report about Haiti has to include the line that 

00:00:08.360 --> 00:00:09.160
it's the poorest country

00:00:09.160 --> 00:00:10.120
in the Western Hemisphere.

00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:14.600
But hold on for a second. Something's missing in this conversation, right?

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:17.280
We need to be all thinking about the relationship

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:20.280
of what we're calling poverty in Haiti

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:21.520
and the relation to the richness

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:22.680
of the rest of world.

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:25.400
And how did the rest of the world get so rich?

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:27.560
Let's start with France.

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:31.600
Imagine if you were enslaved
and after fighting for your independence,

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.000
you were forced to spend
the next couple of generations

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.280
paying compensation to

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:36.840
those who colonized you.

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:39.120
Reparations for slaveholders is a new one for me.

00:00:39.120 --> 00:00:41.720
That is exactly what happened to Haiti.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:43.160
This is punishment

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:44.760
for their unwillingness

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:46.840
to remain under the yoke of slavery.

00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:50.800
In 1697, France and Spain ended a war
with each other

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:53.520
by dividing up the Spanish colony Hispaniola.

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:56.560
Through the labor of
enslaved Indigenous and Black people, 

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:59.480
Saint-Domingue became
the world's most profitable colony, 

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:02.040
exporting sugar, coffee and indigo. 

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:04.040
Enslaved people in Saint-Domingue

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:05.960
suffered some of the harshest and cruelest

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:08.600
slave punishments in the entire Atlantic world.

00:01:08.600 --> 00:01:11.320
Life expectancy was extremely low,

00:01:11.320 --> 00:01:12.680
such that at the moment

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:14.840
of the Haitian Revolution breaking out

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:16.640
in August of 1791,

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:19.000
the vast majority of enslaved people

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:20.640
had only been on the island for

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:22.200
two or three years.

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:27.080
They were from whatever nation
that they had been captive and brought over.

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:28.720
And they basically said no.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:32.600
Self-liberated Africans
led the Haitian Revolution and ended slavery

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:35.600
in present-day Haiti and the Dominican Republic.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:40.480
After 12 years of fighting the French colonial power, which had tried to reintroduce slavery, 

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:44.720
the formerly enslaved people of Saint-Domingue officially declared independence 

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:46.560
and renamed their country Haiti.

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:50.680
Many countries, including the United States, refused to recognize Haitian

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:53.360
independence in fear of slave rebellions.

00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:57.480
And France refused to
accept Haiti's independence unless

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:02.200
Haiti paid 150 million franc as so-called compensation

00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:04.480
for lost revenues from slavery.

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:07.480
That was around 10 times Haiti's annual budget.

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:12.360
But Haiti couldn't decline the indemnity request since the French came ready for war,

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:15.640
carrying more than 500 cannons on their ships.

00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:19.440
Articles from that period show that the French king knew the Haitian government

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:23.720
wouldn't be able to repay the debt, which decimated Haiti's economy.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:29.400
Haitians had extremely high taxes, and most of the tax revenue was paid for the indemnity.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.680
This left the education system,
public infrastructures 

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:34.400
and health care underdeveloped.

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:36.400
Agricultural land was also depleted 

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:40.360
to grow cash crops that pay for the debt
but couldn't feed the country.

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:43.880
It took Haiti 122 years to pay off its debt

00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:45.840
and required taking high-interest loans.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:47.520
It's a self-fulfilling prophecy

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:49.640
to say that Haiti is poor

00:02:49.640 --> 00:02:51.000
and Haiti must be poor. 

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
And I think the better question whenever a people,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.240
an entire people is characterized as poor

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:58.240
with this word is to say,

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:00.800
not “why are they poor?” but “why aren't you?”

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.240
But it's not just the French who have played a role in Haiti's misery.

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.800
So the United States has intervened

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:08.720
in Haitian affairs quite a lot.

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:12.000
President Moïse's assassination in 2021

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:13.400
left some Haitian officials

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:15.080
calling for U.S. intervention. 

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:16.960
But not everyone agrees.

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:19.640
The only way that that could ever even have

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:20.760
a fruitful outcome

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:23.560
would be if it was because they were in dialogue

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:25.040
with the Haitian people for the first time.

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:26.960
Because that is not what usually happens.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:28.360
That's not what happens at all.

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:31.160
They dialogue with the people claiming power

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.720
and some negotiation is struck

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:35.800
between those vying for power

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:37.000
and the United States government.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:38.520
There's a lot of people saying, no,

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:41.120
we don't want the United States to come and

00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:42.360
intervene again 

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:45.320
because this is, again, a repetition of history.

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:48.120
The history that Professor Daut is talking about 

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:51.720
involves the United States
19-year occupation of Haiti,

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:55.440
 an occupation that killed thousands of Haitians. 

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:57.320
Following the assassination of Haiti's president

00:03:57.320 --> 00:03:58.680
in 1915, 

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:01.320
U.S. President Woodrow Wilson's administration

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:03.640
invaded Haiti to protect U.S. investments.

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:07.560
Then, they forced the election of a new Haitian president who would protect

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:09.440
American interests in the country.

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:13.200
Racist and fear-mongering rhetoric
was used to justify the move.

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:15.080
The occupation ensured that the U.S.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:19.600
prioritized its own interests in Haiti
over what was best for Haitians.

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:22.800
The U.S. occupation ended in 1934

00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:26.840
after local dissent and rebellion
grew too costly for the U.S. to control.

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:30.080
But even after the occupation,
the United States continued

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:32.280
to play a role in the internal affairs of Haiti.

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:34.360
In 1957, the U.S. government 

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:37.480
threw its support behind a Haitian dictator -

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:42.240
Duvalier and his successor,
aka his son Jean-Claude, ate up

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:46.680
aid from the United States in exchange for their strong anti-communist stand

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:48.360
at the height of the Cold War.

00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:51.320
Haitian uprisings ended Duvalier Jr.'s rule,

00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:54.800
and led to Haiti choosing
its democratically elected leader,

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:57.360
Jean-Bertrand Aristide, in 1990.

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:01.000
But within a year, Aristide's government was toppled by a coup.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.440
Not only was one of the leaders of the coup
on the CIA's payroll,

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:09.760
but the U.S. had set up and funded the Haitian military and national intelligence service, 

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:11.720
which both played key roles in the coup.

00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:15.480
Ousted Aristide returned to
his second presidency in 2001

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.000
and again was forced out of office
by a coup that he claimed

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.720
the U.S. had orchestrated.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:23.400
And after that,
President Obama's cabinet pressured

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:26.440
a Haitian presidential candidate
to withdraw in 2010.

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:27.960
We see reports coming out of

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:30.480
various civil society organizations saying

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:31.840
that Haitians have lost faith

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:33.760
in the electoral process because it doesn't

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:36.160
reflect their actual concerns.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:40.000
And that brought us to the 2016 Haitian presidential election,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
where late President Moïse was elected with an extremely low voter turnout,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.440
but U.S. backing.

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:50.080
In February 2021, Moïse refused to step down
at the end of his term.

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:55.360
The U.S. once again backed him while thousands of Haitian protesters took to the streets.

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:57.360
&lt;i&gt;[protesters chanting]&lt;/i&gt;

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:58.320
- Many Haitians are saying,

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:02.560
we want to try actual Haitian democracy, 

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:03.840
where the Haitian people,

00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:06.000
not just the elite and the bourgeoisie

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.280
and the business interests,

00:06:07.280 --> 00:06:10.040
get to have a say and determine the direction

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:11.240
and future of the country.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:15.200
It's clear that Haiti's poverty and political instability has long

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:17.520
been influenced and shaped by foreign players.

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:21.120
So knowing this, where does Haiti go from here?

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:23.520
We have never been able to see what could happen 

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:25.320
 in this particular Black country

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:26.720
without meddling and interference.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:28.960
We should try something new in the United States 

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:31.640
and that is back off and back away

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:34.360
and let the Haitian people determine their

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:35.720
own future.

